{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626079"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:33:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:33:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17056"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17056"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.47,0,0.26,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9746"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77014"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9746"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17056"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62520"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5293"},{"type":"tags","id":"9988"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22924"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23102"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77014"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHydroxychloroquine is commonly prescribed as a disease-modifying antirheumatic medication for autoimmune conditions such as systemic lupus erythematosus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of hydroxychloroquine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increases pH within lysosomes and endosomes","Suppresses T lymphocyte proliferation","Depletes B lymphocytes","Neutralises autoantibodies","Inhibits prostaglandin synthesis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHydroxychloroquine primarily works by \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreasing pH within lysosomes and endosomes\u003C/strong\u003E. As a weak base, it accumulates in these acidic cellular compartments, raising their pH. This interferes with antigen processing and presentation, thereby reducing immune system activation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuppresses T lymphocyte proliferation\u003C/strong\u003E: although hydroxychloroquine may have downstream effects on T cells, its primary mechanism involves pH changes in intracellular compartments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDepletes B lymphocytes\u003C/strong\u003E: this mechanism is characteristic of B cell-depleting therapies such as rituximab, rather than hydroxychloroquine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeutralises autoantibodies\u003C/strong\u003E: hydroxychloroquine does not directly interact with or neutralise autoantibodies in the circulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits prostaglandin synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E: this describes the mechanism of non-steroidal anti-inflammatory medications, which is distinct from hydroxychloroquine\u0027s action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy interfering with antigen processing and presentation, hydroxychloroquine reduces immune system activation and inflammation, making it effective for treating autoimmune conditions like systemic lupus erythematosus and rheumatoid arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hydroxychloroquine acts as an immunomodulator by increasing pH in intracellular compartments and interfering with antigen processing.","Hydroxychloroquine accumulates in acidic cellular compartments like lysosomes and endosomes.","The immunomodulatory effects of hydroxychloroquine make it useful in treating autoimmune conditions like systemic lupus erythematosus and rheumatoid arthritis."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62520"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17056"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62520"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T22:21:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T22:22:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9746"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77014"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":